\6 Yes, bitcoin is deadly serious with big fortunes, egos, and ambitions in play.  But thinking of it as an infinite game can help engender the playfulness required for creativity, innovation, progress.  To a beautiful game...

\5 Imagine other games if they were like bitcoin:  * A news industry in which those with the incentive to lie don't because it's more profitable to tell the truth.  * Societies which don't pollute because it's cheaper to be clean.  * Making people free making people money.

\4 Preventing cheating is important in infinite games because cheaters are seeking to win, not to continue play.  Cheating in bitcoin isn't prevented by referees (3rd parties) or parents (the state).  Mathematics, energy & the greed of other players ensures the game continues.

\3 Like any game, bitcoin is an opt-in set of rules devised by its players.  Once the game has begun, changing rules is tough. Only rules which help players continue playing will survive. And no one is in charge of making changes.  So, like the game of culture, Bitcoin evolves.

\2 Bitcoin IS a game, but an *infinite* one, where the goal is to keep playing -- not a finite game where the goal is to win.  "Finite games are theatrical, necessitating an audience; infinite ones are dramatic, involving participants"   https://t.co/ijytf7FaTY

\1 "#Bitcoin is a game we play where we can easily tell when someone is cheating."  When I first saw this (in some ELI5 bitcoin Tweet) I thought it just some pithy phrase.  But over time this simple sentence has come to resonate with me as a profound summary of the bitcoin ethos.

So, also like Bitcoin, when you run Bisq, you become master of your own node on a peer-to-peer network.  Except instead of validating blocks for the Bitcoin network, you provide liquidity to the Bisq network.

Like Bitcoin, Bisq is open-source software.  You don't trade on a website‚Äîyou trade on a program on your computer directly with others on a peer-to-peer network.  It's kind of like bittorrent, but for bitcoin.
